{{Infobox book <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = Misbehaving | title_orig = | translator = | image = File:Misbehaving_Book_Cover.jpg | caption = | author = [[Richard Thaler]] | cover_artist = | country = [[United States of America]] | language = English | genre = | publisher = [[W. W. Norton & Company]] | release_date = | media_type = Print | isbn = 978-0-393-08094-0 | isbn_note = (Hardcover) | oclc = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} '''Misbehaving: The Making of Behavioral Economics''' is a book by [[Richard Thaler]], economist and professor at the University of Chicago's Booth School of Business.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/06/business/dealbook/book-review-misbehaving-by-richard-thaler.html|title=In ‘Misbehaving,’ an Economics Professor Isn’t Afraid to Attack His Own|first=Jonathan A.|last=Knee|date=5 May 2015|publisher=|via=www.nytimes.com}}</ref> He won the Nobel Prize for economics in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/economic-sciences/laureates/2017/press.html|title=Press Release|}}</ref>
The book builds on Thaler's work as a Behavioral Economist in trying to present an alternate view point that humans bring along behavioral biases, are error prone, and are not always rational. This view point builds on his work from his previous book, [[Nudge (book)|Nudge]] published in 2008. Thaler ties this to the effect on markets, which are otherwise expected to be efficient.
Thaler uses the book to talk to readers about how behavioral economic analysis can help look at areas ranging from household finance, to TV shows, NFL drafts and emerging disruptive businesses like Uber, in a new light.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Misbehaving.html?id=CorKoQEACAAJ|title=Misbehaving: The Making of Behavioral Economics|first=Richard H.|last=Thaler|date=9 October 2017|publisher=W.W. Norton|via=Google Books}}</ref>
